1.3 Briefly describe in your own words what each of the 10 parameters of the cell nuclei mean, using the documentation of the dataset in scikit-learn, the paper of the original collectors of the data set, and the example image in Figure 1.

  • Scikit-learn: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/datasets/index.html#breast-cancer-dataset
  • Paper: https://minds.wisconsin.edu/bitstream/1793/59692/1/TR1131.pdf

Answer

The nuclear features include:

  1. Radius - The average of radial line segements which are the lengths between the centroid of the snake and th indivisual point. This is put more simply by the scikit database as the mean radius.
  2. Perimeter - The total distance around the snake points.
  3. Area - A count of the pixels within snake points and an additional half of a pixel for every pixel in the perimeter.
  4. Compactness - The squared perimeter divided by the area minus 1. This unit aims to measure shape irregularity, the authors comment on its short comings.
  5. Smoothness - Another unit to measure irregularity based on changes in radius.
  6. Concavity - A measure of nucleus concavity/indentation with an emphasis on indentations within smaller areas of the nucleus. The authors point out larger indentations are picked up in other features.
  7. Concave Points - A count of the number of concave points/indentations.
  8. Symmetry - A measure of distance differences between perpendicular lines along the longest split of a nucleus.
  9. Fractural dimension - This measures the perimeters of a nucleus when you use fewer and fewer lines to measure it. These are then plotted on a log scale and the slope value minus 1 is taken as the value.
  10. Texture - Determined and measured by standard deviation in greyscale colour intenisities.

1.4 How are the classes Malignant (cancer) and Benign (healthy) encoded in the dataset? What is the default assumption for label coding of sklearn.metrics.precision_score? How will you handle the label coding?

Answer

The class distribution according to the Scikit database is: 212 - Malignant, 357 - Benign

In [4]:
df.target.value_counts().to_dict()
Out[4]:
{(1,): 357, (0,): 212}

As you can see from the above, 0 is indicative of malignancy and 1 is benign. In sklearn.metrics.precision_score, the parameter 'pos_label' would need to be set to 0 instead of the default 1. As we're determining malignancy, this will mark the occurrence of 0 as a positive occurrence.

# Producing the ROC curve for all features and presenting in three groups of 10
## Assigning variables
feature_groups = [mean_clean, error_clean, worst_clean]  
titles = ["Features relating to mean", "Features relating to error", "Features relating to worst value"]
figure = 0
roc_auc_values = {}

## Creating figures, each to populate with 10 features
for group in feature_groups:
    plt.figure(figsize = (5,5))
    plt.title(titles[feature_groups.index(group)] +"\n")
    figure =+ 1
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], '--', color=('grey'))  # Adds the diagonal representing a feature with poor predictive power     
    
    # Calculating values and plotting the ROC for each feature
    for feature in group:
        y_pred =  df[feature].values
        y_true = df.target.values.astype(int)

        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_true, y_pred, pos_label = 0)
        
        # Storing the area under the curve for each feature
        roc_auc = metrics.auc(fpr, tpr)
        roc_auc_values[feature]=roc_auc
        
        # Plotting the value
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, lw=1, label=feature +' ROC (area = %0.2f)' % (roc_auc))
        plt.xlim([-0.05, 1.05])
        plt.ylim([-0.05, 1.05])
        plt.grid()
        plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
        plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
        plt.legend(loc="best", fontsize = 10)

1.7 Which of the parameters seems promising based on the histograms and ROC curves? Justify your choice while referring to the particular features in the figures that indicate a good separation. Choose your top five candidate features.

Answer

We are looking for features that have seperate populations in the histogram, and reach the upper left hand side on the ROC curve (or area under the graph close to a value of 1. This region of the ROC represents a feature with a high true positive rate and a low false negative rate meaning it will identify most cases but not be over zealous in producing positive results.

Of the 10 nuclear features, the radius, perimeter, area, and concave points appear to meet the above requirements. However when it comes to the features needed for the model we need to be more specific. I'll take the five features above that produce the highest area under the ROC value:

In [10]:
top_5 = dict(sorted(roc_auc_values.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse = True))
top_5_listed = list(top_5.items())[:5]
print("The five features that best meet the criteria I've described are:")
for feature, value in top_5_listed:
    print(feature, "(",round(value, 3) ,")" )

The five features that best meet the criteria I've described are:
worst perimeter ( 0.975 )
worst radius ( 0.97 )
worst area ( 0.97 )
worst concave points ( 0.967 )
mean concave points ( 0.964 )

All of the above have good seperation between the two populations in the histograms as well so they are my selected five.

2.2 Explain in your own words what the parameter class_weight does. Set it to “balanced”.

Answer

class_weight places a weighting on the class to account for the frequency of different classes in the data set. In other words, if one class is overly represented it may introduce a bias to the model, by giving a class weighting we can prevent that. In my split, I made sure the training set and test set have similar representation so the weighting should apply well when the model actually gets used.

2.3 Explain in your own words what the parameter learning_rate does and how the learning rate will be adjusted using the selection ‘optimal’. Set it to ‘optimal’.

Answer

Learning_rate controls how quickly the model reaches convergence, or learns. The 'optimal' value aims to balance the convergence time and the accuracy. It uses the inital learning rate as a guide for consecutive iterations.

                 SGDClassifier(class_weight='balanced', penalty='elasticnet',
                               random_state=10))])
StandardScaler()
SGDClassifier(class_weight='balanced', penalty='elasticnet', random_state=10)

Answer

The model interprets value magnitudes, not their relative differences. The standard scaler makes sure all the features are intepretted through the same lens, preventing any features from providing more or less weight than is reasonable relative to other features. This alteration converts values to z-scores (with the mean at 0 and standard deviation of 1). If this scaler isn't applied then features with larger values may take priority over other features and lead to a misinformed model.

3.4 Summarise what can be seen in the 5x5 scatter plots. Do the two classes appear well separable and where can we see this in the plots? Is the classifier doing a good job and why?

Answer

When it comes to the training set the predominant colours in all plots are green and light blue indicating accurate classification. There is good seperation observed in each figure but not complete isolation. This is to be expected, otherwise it would be simple for a clinican to categorise by eye. However, the test set demonstrates something else entirely. A great deal of instances are labelled as false positives meaning the seperation observed is completely meaningless as the model is overfitting on the training data.

3.5 Based on the 5x5 scatterplots, do you think the linear model is sufficient to separate the two classes, and why? Describe two advantages of using a linear model. Describe two advantages of using a more complex and flexible model, such as a Support Vector Machine (SVM).

Answer

This model is overfitting the training data, it is not adequate for the use case. Almost all instances were marked as positive cases of melanoma. This could be fixed by providing more training data, reducing the features avaliable to the model (perhaps through PCA), or by using a more complex model.

The linear model is good because it can be easily explained and is computationally inexpensive compared to more advanced models. However a more complex model, such as an SVM, will have better accuracy as it can manage more complex or non-linear patterns in the data. They also have a variety of parameters surrounding the boundaries between classes which allows them to generalize well on unseen data.
